\title{Coln as a database}

\p{Coln can work as a little proof assistant which is restricted to positive types, but the real point of this restriction is to enable a translation to the database world.}

\p{One could look at this in two ways, depending on whether you think of the language or the database as “primary.”}

\p{In one sense, because the database engine can be used to reason about models defined purely in Coln, the database engine is essentially a souped-up tactic (in the sense of Rocq or Lean) for enumerating the elements of types.}

\p{But not all models of Coln theories need to be defined in Coln itself. As we have seen, the automatically-produced TypeScript functions can be used to initialize and populate a model in an imperative style. For instance, when using Coln to do an egglog-style analysis of a C-like language, one would first write a parser and type checker in a normal programming language, and then issue mutations via the API to create a model that represented the IR of the program. Then Coln queries could be run against that IR to resolve questions about the behavior of the program.}

\p{Thus, Coln is not a typical proof assistant; Coln is a tool that is meant to be integrated into a larger program that is not written in Coln.}

\p{In order to give the programmer a mental model for how they can expect these commands to work, in this section of the manual we describe the translation from a theory in the [Coln language](000L) to a collection of tables.}

